  "prompt": "What is headward erosion?",
  "response": "**Headward erosion** is a geological process in which the **headwaters**, or source, of a river or stream erodes the land in an **upstream direction**, extending the length of the watercourse. This type of erosion occurs primarily at the **head** (uppermost part) of a stream and is driven by factors such as **gravity**, **water flow**, and the **steepness of the slope**.  \n\nAs water flows downhill, it erodes the soil and bedrock at the stream's head, causing the **channel to lengthen** and the **valley to extend** backward into the surrounding landscape. This process often leads to the formation of features like **gullies** or **ravines** and can significantly alter the topography over time.  \n\nHeadward erosion is a key mechanism in the **evolution of drainage systems** and contributes to the **capture** of smaller streams or tributaries by larger ones, a process known as **stream piracy**.",
